Theory¶

Paper (2015): https://arxiv.org/pdf/1505.04597.pdf

U-Net is a network architecture used for semantic image segmentation. Originally was developed for medical data clustering, but applicable in all other settings.

The output of the newtork is 2 scores for each pixel of the image that predict 2 classes: Background / Object.

Model architecture looks like letter "U", that's why it got its name.

The network advances the FPN (Fully Convolutional Network, 2014) architecture.

It shares FPNs main features:

  • There is a contracting (or downsampling, or encoder) part that tries to model the semantics of the image
  • There is an expanding (or upsampling, or decoder) part that tries to refine segmentation boundaries
  • Encoder layers are directly connected to corresponding decoder layers and provide context for better boundary refinement

But there are couple of differences:

  • the network has been made more symmetric, "expantion" part became a reflection of the "contraction" part

In general setting there could be more than 2 classes for semantic segmentation. In that case each pixel is assigned to either background class or one of N classes (cars / trees / pedestrians / houses)

Applications of semantic image segmentation:

  1. scene segmentation for self-driving cars
  2. medical imaging
  3. aerial photography / farming / geology

Datasets:

  • Cityscapes
  • https://www.kaggle.com/c/tgs-salt-identification-challenge/overview

References: https://nanonets.com/blog/semantic-image-segmentation-2020/

Practice¶

Quick notes about implementation:

  • All tensor operations in the network follow the same pattern thus they can be conveniently allocated in blocks
    • contraction blocks
    • intermediate layers
    • expansion blocks
  • The authors opted to use no padding in covolutions (i.e. "valid" padding mode); To prevent unncessary cropping and make the task more simple padding can be safely changed to "same";

  • Because of that, the output size of the network (388 x 388) is less than original (572 x 572) image size. To correctly process the whole image, the authors artificially enhance edges with mirrored data before processing (left);

  • In medical imaging, segments tend to stick to each other throughout a thin border. These boarders are hard to predict, so authors modified the loss function and gave more weight to such areas => weighted loss fucntion. This made the model make more effort on correctly classifying borders.
  • Training on sparse data requires a lot of augmentation

PyTorch¶

Let's define a paired convolution block - a sequence of 2 convolutions followed by ReLU activation

In [22]:
import torch
import torch.nn as nn

def conv_block(in_channels, out_channels):
  return nn.Sequential(
      nn.Conv2d(in_channels, out_channels, kernel_size=3),
      nn.ReLU(inplace=True),
      nn.Conv2d(out_channels, out_channels, kernel_size=3),
      nn.ReLU(inplace=True)
  )

Now let's assemble the "encoder" part;

In [118]:
class UNet(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self):
      super(UNet, self).__init__()
    
    def forward(self, image_tensor):
      
      # Encoder part
      
      x1 = conv_block(1,64)(image_tensor)
      x2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x1)
      
      x3 = conv_block(64,128)(x2)
      x4 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x3)
      
      x5 = conv_block(128,256)(x4)
      x6 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x5)
      
      x7 = conv_block(256,512)(x6)
      x8 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x7)
      
      x9 = conv_block(512,1024)(x8)
            
      return x9

The output of the encoder should be (1024 x 388 x 388)

Cropping¶

Since all convolutions are unpadded, they loose 2 pixels on each dimension. So in order to concatenate back during upconvolution, we'll have to crop a feature map from the encoder.

In [106]:
def crop_features(encoder_features, decoder_features):
  edge_size = (encoder_features.shape[2] - decoder_features.shape[2]) // 2
  return encoder_features[:, :, edge_size : encoder_features.shape[2] - edge_size, edge_size : encoder_features.shape[3] - edge_size]

Define upsampling logic

In [110]:
def upconv_block(decoder_image, encoder_image, in_channels, out_channels):
  
  # Upconvolve image features
  upconv = nn.ConvTranspose2d(in_channels,  out_channels, kernel_size=2, stride=2)  
  decoder_image_upsampled = upconv(decoder_image)
  
  # print("upsampled to {}".format(decoder_image_upsampled.shape))
  # print("counterpart size = {}".format(encoder_image.shape))
  
  # Crop the encoder counterpart
  encoder_image_cropped = crop_features(encoder_image, decoder_image_upsampled)
  # print("after image crop = {}".format(encoder_image_cropped.shape))
  
  # Concatenate decoder and encoder images
  decoder_image_concatenated = torch.cat([encoder_image_cropped, decoder_image_upsampled], 1)
  
  # Convolve twice
  result = conv_block(in_channels, out_channels)(decoder_image_concatenated)
  
  return result

Now let's assemble the decoder part

In [111]:
class UNet(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self):
      super(UNet, self).__init__()
    
    def forward(self, image_tensor):
      
      
      # Encoder part
      
      x1 = conv_block(1,64)(image_tensor)
      x2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x1)
      
      x3 = conv_block(64,128)(x2)
      x4 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x3)
      
      x5 = conv_block(128,256)(x4)
      x6 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x5)
      
      x7 = conv_block(256,512)(x6)
      x8 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x7)
      
      x9 = conv_block(512,1024)(x8)
      
      
      # Decoder part
      
      x10 = upconv_block(x9,  x7, in_channels = 1024, out_channels = 512)
      x11 = upconv_block(x10, x5, in_channels = 512, out_channels = 256)
      x12 = upconv_block(x11, x3, in_channels = 256, out_channels = 128)
      x13 = upconv_block(x12, x1, in_channels = 128, out_channels = 64)
            
      return x13

Finally we need to define 1x1 convolution with 2 output chennels (background / object)

In [115]:
class UNet(nn.Module):
    
    def __init__(self):
      super(UNet, self).__init__()
      
    
    def forward(self, image_tensor):
      
      
      # Encoder part
      
      x1 = conv_block(1,64)(image_tensor)
      x2 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x1)
      
      x3 = conv_block(64,128)(x2)
      x4 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x3)
      
      x5 = conv_block(128,256)(x4)
      x6 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x5)
      
      x7 = conv_block(256,512)(x6)
      x8 = nn.MaxPool2d(kernel_size=2, stride=2)(x7)
      
      x9 = conv_block(512,1024)(x8)
      
      
      # Decoder part
      
      x10 = upconv_block(x9,  x7, in_channels = 1024, out_channels = 512)
      x11 = upconv_block(x10, x5, in_channels = 512, out_channels = 256)
      x12 = upconv_block(x11, x3, in_channels = 256, out_channels = 128)
      x13 = upconv_block(x12, x1, in_channels = 128, out_channels = 64)
      
      
      # Output layer
      
      x14 = nn.Conv2d(in_channels=64, out_channels=2, kernel_size = 1)(x13)
      
      return x14

Let's define a function that converts an image mask to a 20-class tensor

In [243]:
from tqdm.notebook import tqdm

def get_target(mask):
  img_mask = numpy.array(mask.getdata()).reshape(mask.width, mask.height, 3)
  target_tensor = torch.zeros(mask.width, mask.height, 3)
  for x in range(mask.width):
    for y in range(mask.height):
      pixel = (img_mask[x,y,0], img_mask[x,y,1], img_mask[x,y,2])
      if pixel == (0,0,0):
          continue
      target = target_dict[pixel] if pixel in target_dict else 0
      target_tensor[x,y,0] = 1
      target_tensor[x,y,1] = 1
      target_tensor[x,y,2] = 1
  return target_tensor
      
result = get_target(voc_dataset[0][1].convert(mode='RGB'))

Keras¶














Let's do the same thing in Keras;


This time we will be using "SAME" padding mode













In [2]:



    


from keras import Model
from keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping, ModelCheckpoint, ReduceLROnPlateau
from keras.optimizers import Adam
from keras.layers import Input, Conv2D, Conv2DTranspose, MaxPooling2D, concatenate, Dropout

def convolution_block(output_channels, input_tensor, dropout=False):
  conv1 = Conv2D(output_channels, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same")(input_tensor)
  conv2 = Conv2D(output_channels, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same")(conv1)	
  return conv2

def convolution_pooling(input, dropout):
    pool = MaxPooling2D((2, 2))(input)
    if dropout:
        pool = Dropout(0.25)(pool)
    return pool
    
def deconvolution_block(output_channels, input, conv):
    deconv = Conv2DTranspose(output_channels, (3, 3), strides=(2, 2), padding="same")(input)
    uconv = concatenate([deconv, conv])
    uconv = Dropout(0.5)(uconv)
    uconv = Conv2D(output_channels, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same")(uconv)
    uconv = Conv2D(output_channels, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same")(uconv)
    return uconv

# Input
input_layer = Input((128, 128, 1))

# Contraction Part
conv1 = convolution_block(64, input_layer)
conv1_pooled = convolution_pooling(conv1, dropout=True)
conv2 = convolution_block(128, conv1_pooled)
conv2_pooled = convolution_pooling(conv2, dropout=True)
conv3 = convolution_block(256, conv2_pooled)
conv3_pooled = convolution_pooling(conv3, dropout=True)
conv4 = convolution_block(512, conv3_pooled)
conv4_pooled = convolution_pooling(conv4, dropout=True)

# Middle Part
convm = Conv2D(1024, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same")(conv4_pooled)
convm = Conv2D(1024, (3, 3), activation="relu", padding="same")(convm)

# Expansion Part
uconv4 = deconvolution_block(512, convm, conv4)
uconv3 = deconvolution_block(256, uconv4, conv3)
uconv2 = deconvolution_block(128, uconv3, conv2)
uconv1 = deconvolution_block(64, uconv2, conv1)
    
# Output
output_layer = Conv2D(1, (1,1), padding="same", activation="sigmoid")(uconv1)

model = Model(input_layer, output_layer)

model.compile(loss="binary_crossentropy", optimizer="adam", metrics=["accuracy"])
